TY  - JOUR
T1  - Effects of Varying Goal Types and Incentive Systems on Performance and Satisfaction
AU  - London, Manuel
AU  - Oldham, Greg R.
Y1  - 1976/12/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255789
DO  - 10.5465/255789
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 537
EP  - 546
VL  - 19
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Goals for high and minimum acceptable performance were manipulated under three incentive conditions: piece-rate, fixed rate, and no incentive. The nature of the incentive system and the difficulty of the high performance goal independently affected performance. Satisfaction, performance, and the relationship between the two were a function of the level of minimum acceptable performance, attainment and difficulty of the high performance goal. Implications of distinguishing between the effects of different goal types are discussed.
AB  - Goals for high and minimum acceptable performance were manipulated under three incentive conditions: piece-rate, fixed rate, and no incentive. The nature of the incentive system and the difficulty of the high performance goal independently affected performance. Satisfaction, performance, and the relationship between the two were a function of the level of minimum acceptable performance, attainment and difficulty of the high performance goal. Implications of distinguishing between the effects of different goal types are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255789
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255789
